DRAFT

1 Background

Returning natural-origin and hatchery-origin Chinook Salmon to the Lostine River are intercepted by a permanent trapping facility. After each fish is captured, facility staff decide to release the fish either upstream to spawn naturally, or to keep them for future use as brood stock or as an outplant to downstream tributaries to the Wallowa River. The decision to release the fish upstream or to keep them is guided by a weir management sliding scale that seeks to balance the contributions of natural-origin fish to hatchery production, and hatchery-origin fish to natural production at various escapement levels. We initiated this work to more thoroughly understand the impacts of the weir management sliding scale on total returns and allotted harvest. Because the weir sliding scale limits the number or proportion of hatchery origin spawners (pHOS) we hypothesized removing the constraint of pHOS would increase natural production and total returns to the Lostine River, and ultimately a greater number of fish available for harvest.

We developed a life-cycle simulation model to examine differences in escapement and harvest under five management scenarios. The first scenario follows our current baseline conditions with an integrated hatchery program of 175 brood stock with spawner composition determined by the weir management sliding scale, and harvest being implemented at the maximum allowed level determined by harvest sliding scales. The second scenario used the weir sliding scale to determine the same number of natural-origin broodstock as scenario 1, but differed by allowing an unconstrained pHOS (i.e., all remaining hatchery origin fish were allowed to spawn naturally). The third scenario used the same weir sliding scale as scenario 1 to determine brood stock and naturally spawning composition but didnâ€™t allow harvest (i.e., set harvest to zero). The forth and fifth scenarios eliminated the hatchery program and assumed all fish spawned naturally and only differed by either allowing harvest or excluding harvest.

2 Results and Conclusions

2.1 Weir Management Sliding Scale

  1. Under the current baseline conditions the model stabilizes at:
  2. 1,500 hatchery-origin fish and 500 natural-origin fish returning,
  3. harvest or natural-origin adults is 19, and 150 hatchery-origin adults are harvested.
  4. Hatchery-origin escapement is unchanged when the weir management sliding scale is removed, or when harvest is not allowed.
  5. Natural-origin escapement is approximately 250 individuals without the hatchery program (i.e., half the return with the hatchery program).
  6. Zero harvest occurs without the hatchery program.

3 Methods

3.1 Life-cycle Model

The developed model incorporates 5 life stages and introduces stochasticity using a Monte-Carlo simulation approach. The simulation randomly samples variables from assumed probability distributions to gain inference about an unknown outcome (Gentle 2015). Our model design follows a stream type Chinook salmon life cycle in Idaho (Groot and Margolis 1991) and includes stock-recruit functions to control for unlimited growth at the juvenile stage (Ricker 1975), smolt-to-adult return rates (Sandford and Smith 2002), and age compositions estimated from Lostine River observed data NEED CITATION FOR ADULTS AND JUVENILES. After drawing random variables from each assumed distribution we then use them in deterministic functions to draw probabilistic inferences at life stages of interest (Manly and Manly 2017).

Model inputs cover five key areas: (1) supplementation program design and weir management, (2) spawner success and juvenile productivity, (3) smolt-to-adult return rates, (4) age composition of adult returns, and (5) tributary harvest exploitation rates. Model outputs include total tributary abundance by origin and age, brood stock collection and spawner composition, and harvest opportunities available for the simulated return.

The model then increments forward with each run year abundance at time (\(t\)) producing brood year returns at \(t+3\), \(t+4\), and \(t+5\) years.

The model initiates with tributary escapement (i.e., the tributary mouth downstream of the hatchery weir) of natural origin (\(NOR\)) and hatchery origin (\(HOR\)) fish returning (\(N^{Trib}_{O,t}\)), where, \(O\) is origin, and \(t\) is run year. Once tributary escapement is determined, the maximum proportion of adult (i.e., age 4 and 5 fish only) hatchery-origin spawners (\(pHOS\)) allowed upstream of the weir, and the proportion of natural-origin adults allowed within the hatchery brood stock (\(pNOB\)) is set using the \(\sum_{A=4,5}N^{Trib}_{O,A,t}\), where \(A\) is age, and the agreed upon weir management sliding scale (3.1)(NEED CITATION).

Table 3.1: Lostine River weir management sliding scale sets the allowed proportions of natural-origin brood stock (pNOB) and hatchery-origin spawners (pHOS) based on a viable abundance of 500 adults and the estimated return of natural-origin adults.
NOR Adults < Maximum pNOB Minimum pNOB Maximum pHOS
8 0.00 0.00 1.00
75 0.50 0.00 1.00
150 0.40 0.20 0.70
250 0.40 0.25 0.60
500 0.30 0.30 0.50
750 0.30 0.40 0.40
1000 0.25 0.50 0.25
Inf 0.25 1.00 0.10

Actual fish arriving to the hatchery weir is influenced by tributary escapement and the number of fish harvested upstream of the mouth, yet downstream of the weir. Harvest includes the sum of tribal and sport-fishing impacts.

For tribal harvest, we assume the number of NOR and HOR adult fish harvested (\(H^{Tribe}_{O,t}\)) is the maximum allowed rate determined by the adult only tributary escapement, \(\sum_{A=4,5}N^{Trib}_{O,A,t}\) and the agreed upon tribal tributary harvest exploitation rates (NEED CITATION). Table 3.2 shows tribal harvest exploitation rates used for adult fish, where the number harvested equals the lowest rate times the abundance in the lower bracket plus the abundance in excess of the lower rate times the higher rate. For example, if the natural-origin return was 500 adults, then harvest would equal \((300 * .01) + (500 - 300) * .08 = 19\).

Table 3.2: Tributary harvest rate on surplus fish greater than the closest lower rate.
Abundance Natural Harvest Rate Hatchery Harvest Rate
<300 0.01 0.02
<1000 0.08 0.09
<1500 0.16 0.18
<2000 0.19 0.21
>2000 0.28 0.40

Sport-fishing harvest is determined by \(\sum_{A=4,5}N^{Trib}_{O,A,t}\) and the FMEP NEEDS WORK/CORRECTED AND A CITATION.

After harvest is removed, the number of adult fish surviving to the weir (\(N^{Weir}_{O,A,t}\)) and available for brood stock collection and release upstream becomes

\[ N^{Weir}_{O,A,t} = \sum_{A=4,5}(N^{Trib}_{O,A,t}) - H_{O,t} \] where, \(H_{O,t}\) represents the number of adults harvested by tribal and sports fisherman.

The number of natural-origin adults removed for brood stock (\(BS_{NOR,t}\)) is then calculated with the designated \(pNOB\) from the weir management sliding scale (3.1) and the available adults at the weir.

\[ BS_{NOR,t} = N^{Weir}_{NOR,A,t} * pNOB \] Hatchery-origin brood stock (\(BS_{HOR,t}\)) becomes the remainder of the total brood stock need (\(BS\)).

\[ BS_{HOR_t} = BS - BS_{NOR,t} \]

Remaining natural-origin adult fish are released upstream (\(N^{Released}_{NOR}\)) of the weir and are available to spawn naturally,

\[ N^{Released}_{NOR,t} = N^{Weir}_{NOR,A,t} - BS_{NOR,t} \] while, hatchery-origin fish released upstream (\(N^{Released}_{HOR,t}\)) to spawn naturally is controlled by the weir management sliding scale (3.1) and set to the maximum proportion of hatchery-origin spawners (\(pHOS_{max}\)).

\[ N^{Released}_{HOR,t} = \frac{(-pHOS_{max,t} * N^{Released}_{NOR,t})}{pHOS_{max,t} - 1}. \]

Excess hatchery-origin adults that were not kept for brood stock or released upstream are removed from the system and not available to produce progeny.

Once fish are designated into the correct spawning environment, natural or hatchery, The total number of fish successfully contributing to juvenile production (\(S_{O,t}\)) is then a random variable from a binomial distribution with an assumed prespawn mortality rate (\(p_O\)) and the number of adults in the spawning environment;

\[ S_{NOR,t} \sim Binomial(p_O, N^{Released}_{NOR,t} + N^{Released}_{HOR,t}) \] and

\[ S_{HOR,t} \sim Binomial(p_O, BS_{NOR,t} + BS_{HOR,t}). \] Natural origin juvenile smolt (\(J_{NOR,t}\)) surviving to Lower Granite Dam is sampled from a multivariate normal distribution with a vector of Beverton-Holt density-dependent (Ricker 1975) coefficients and covariance matrix as the mean (\(\mu_{BH}\)) and shape (\(\Sigma_{BH}\)) parameters (Casella and Berger 2021).

\[ J_{NOR,t} \sim MVN(\mu_{BH}, \Sigma_{BH}) \] While hatchery origin juvenile smolt \(J^{HOR,t}\) surviving to Lower Granite Dam is assumed to follow a non-density dependent function, where, stochasticity is introduced by sampling the ratio of hatchery smolts to hatchery spawners (\(\phi_t\)) from a log-normal distribution.

\[ \phi_t \sim LogNormal(\mu_\phi, \sigma_\phi) \]

With \(\mu_\phi\) and \(\sigma_\phi\) representing the mean and standard deviation of the natural logged transformed ratio. Hatchery origin juvenile smolt surviving to Lower Granite Dam then becomes

\[ J_{HOR,t} = S_{HOR,t} * \phi_t. \] The proportion of brood year smolts at Lower Granite Dam that escape to the tributary (\(\pi_{O,t}\); i.e., SAR) is sampled on the logit scale from a multivariate normal distribution, where, \(\bf{\mu_{SAR}}\) is a vector of mean SARs for each origin, and \(\Sigma_{SAR}\) is the covariance matrix. (Casella and Berger 2021).

\[ logit(\pi_{O,t}) \sim MVN(\bf{\mu_{SAR}}, \Sigma_{SAR}) \]

Then, the total brood year (\(BY\)) progeny return to the tributary from year \(t\) juvenile production is,

\[ P_{O,t} = J_{O,t} * \phi_{O,t}. \]

Progeny returns regardless of origin, were assumed to return across three age classes (3, 4, and 5) following a multinomial distribution,

\[ [P_{A=3}, P_{A=4}, P_{A=5}]_{O,t} \sim Multinomial(A_{O},P_{O,t}), \] with \(A_O\) being the vector of age composition probabilities. Tributary escapement for year \(t\), the starting point of the model, is then the sum of the correct age group progeny return for the correct brood year, as follows,

\[ N^{Trib}_{O,t} = \sum_{A=3,4,5}P_{A, O,t - A}. \]

The life cycle model was written in the statistical computing language R (R Core Team 2014) and available at https://github.com/NPTfisheries/Chinook-Life-Cycle.

3.2 Parameter Estimates

Assumed probability distributions were parameterized with Lostine River juvenile, adult, and survival data collected over the last 23 years (1995-2018) by the Nez Perce Tribeâ€™s Grande Ronde Supplementation Monitoring and Evaluation project.

3.2.1 Successful Spawners

The Beverton-Holt function is parameterized asâ€¦.., where, \(S\) represents the total naturally spawning stock released upstream of the weir, and natural-origin juvenile recruits (\(J_{NOR,t}\)) represent smolt surviving to Lower Granite Dam.

\[ J_{NOR} = \frac{\alpha S}{1 + \beta S} \]

The \(\alpha\) parameter represents the maximum recruitment rate at low spawning abundances and \(\beta\) is the density-dependent parameter that governs the functions shape and carrying capacity (\(k = \frac{\alpha}{\beta}\)).

3.2.3 Smolt-to-Adult Return Rates

We modeled smolt-to-adult return (SAR) rates and their covariance between natural and hatchery origin fish with a linear mixed effects model (Zuur et al. 2009). Similar to Bosch et al. (2023), a logit link was used to estimate the SAR proportions as a linear function of the fixed effect origin and the random effect of brood_year.

3.4 indicates natural origin SARs are typically higher than hatchery origin and range from 0.0064779, 0.0757901. Hatchery origin SARs range from 0.0028418, 0.0436594 and on average are only 41% of the natural origin SAR.

Figure 3.4: Brood year estimates of smolt to adult return (SAR) rates for Lostine River natural and hatchery origin returns. The mean SAR for each origin is shown in black with the associated 95% confidence intervals.

SAR predictions generated from the fitted SAR model are shown in 3.5. Predictions are derived using the uncertainty and covariance in fixed effects parameters and the random brood year effects.

Figure 3.5: Smolt-to-adult return predictions based on the best fitting model and random brood year effects.

3.2.4 Age at Return

Age-at-return was modeled with three age categories (i.e., 3, 4, and 5) using multinomial logistic models (Agresti 2003) with terms for origin, brood year, and the origin by brood year interaction. We determined the full model was the best fit when compared against model subsets with an analysis of deviance. The model indicated natural origin age 3 returns were relatively decreasing while older age 4 and 5 fish are increasing (3.6. Hatchery origin fish showed steep decreases in age 3 and age 5 returns with a steep increase in age 4 returns.
